C11: Illinois Dept. of Human Services is an agency that not only includes the welfare division, but also Mental Health, Development Disabilities,  Rehabilitation Services, and Alcohol and Substance.  The responses in this survey pertain to our Division of Human Capital Development which is responsible for the welfare programs.  We have a couple of locations throughout the state that provide co-located services for all of the programs in our Dept. but most of our field offices administer only the welfare programs.  Other than at those 2 co-located sites, we do not have a formal process for service delivery and sharing customer information.  We are implementing a process of assigning one recipient identification number regardless of the service the customer receives.  But we do not have a common data base for sharing information about the different services received from the various Divisions.   By Illinois law, a person who receives TANF automatically qualifies for medical assistance.  While the medical assistance is authorized by our agency along with the TANF, medical assistance programs are administered by a separate agency, the Dept. of Healthcare and Family Services.

C11: Indiana reconstructed its eligibility determination process in 2007.  The primary change was the implementation of regional change centers to handle reported and the disbursement of cases to regional or county teams instead assignment to a specific caseworker.  Of the big three welfare programs (Medicaid, SNAP and TANF Cash Assistance) administered by our agency, TANF is by far the smallest in terms of individuals served.  Only 7.2% of the 1.3M individuals receiving some type of asssitance are on cash assistance.  Most of our local offices are in building separate from other state programs; howeever, in a few smaller counties our offices are located in the county municipal buildings that include other state programs.
